Europe
---------
[1] UK (HPA report)
Date: Fri 6 Sep 2013
Source: HPA Weekly, Volume 7 No 36 [abbreviated & edited]
http://www.hpa.org.uk/hpr/archives/2013/news3613.htm#msls07


The declining number of laboratory confirmed cases of measles in England observed in May and June 2013 (194 and 116, respectively) continued in July 2013 with a total of 73 cases, bringing the number reported since the start of the year to 1365 cases. The South-West region reported the most cases (33), many of which were associated with an on-going outbreak linked to the Glastonbury music festival. As reported in June 2013, the highest proportion of cases were in children aged 1-4 years (17/73 23 percent), a shift from the 10-14 year age group most affected earlier in the year. The proportion of cases aged 10-16 years (12/73 16 percent) -- the age group targeted in the on-going MMR catch-up campaign -- was similar to that reported in June 2013.

So far this year [2013], 274 (20 percent) cases have been associated with secondary school outbreaks. Small outbreaks have also been reported from "hard-to-reach" populations with known low vaccine coverage such as the travelling community and the ultra-Orthodox Jewish community in north London. Overall, 283 (21 percent) of all cases in 2013 were admitted to hospital; 39 reported complications including pneumonia, meningitis and gastroenteritis.

In England, most of the cases with an onset date in July 2013 that have been sequenced are a D8 genotype. The MVs/Taunton.GBR/27.12/ [D8] strain continues to be the main virus type, but with a cluster of cases of a different D8 strain in the South West region, and sporadic genotype B3 strains in a couple of regions.

As previously reported, the shift towards cases in secondary school age groups during 2013 is likely to be due to the fall in coverage of MMR between 1999 and 2005. To reduce the risk of larger outbreaks of measles in the next academic year, Public Health England, the Department of Health and NHS England announced an MMR catch-up programme in late April 2013. The campaign has targeted children aged between 10 and 16 years who have a record of none or incomplete MMR vaccination. Returns from the NHS Areas Teams confirm that almost 5000 practices have already signed up to participate in the programme. The service involves sending letters from general practices inviting under-vaccinated children to attend the surgery for vaccination. The primary target population was the estimated 8 percent of that age group who had received no vaccine (around 1/3rd of a million); secondary targets included a similar number of that age group who had received one dose of MMR and a similar number of children in other age groups.

Data has been extracted from just over 2000 practices (around a quarter of the total) on the MMR status of children turning 10 to 16 years of age in July 2013. Comparing this with children aged 9-15 years in 2012, it suggests that the proportion recorded as unvaccinated fell by around 1.5 percent (representing around 17 000 children in the participating practices). If this progress was replicated nationally, this suggests that around 65 000 unvaccinated children have received MMR since last year [2012]. The proportion recorded as having received 2 doses of MMR has increased by 2.2 percent. Although some of this may represent data cleaning, this scale of increase is consistent with the vaccine ordering data, which suggests that around 200 000 extra doses have been used. So far, most vaccination has been conducted in primary care, although school campaigns were conducted in response to local outbreaks in many areas during the last academic year. Plans are being developed to sustain these activities and to undertake specific programmes in some schools during the next 2 terms.

