[4] USA (AZ)
Date: Thu 5 Sep 2013
Source: The Yuma Sun [edited]
http://www.yumasun.com/articles/vaccinations-89484-measles-cases.html


Public health officials are concerned about a once-common childhood illness that appears to be making a comeback in the USA. Measles once killed one in every 1000 infected. In the United States alone, the childhood infection killed 500 Americans a year at its peak, according to USA Today. Measles can lead to bronchitis, encephalitis or pneumonia, according to the National Library of Medicine, and complications can lead to death. Thanks to vaccinations, however, the disease was stopped in its tracks, with officials calling it eradicated in the Western hemisphere.

However, nationwide there has been a growing trend of parents who refuse to get vaccinations for their children. And now, the nation has seen 125 cases of measles so far this year [2013]. At least 25 cases have been reported in Texas linked to a church whose senior pastor was critical of measles vaccinations. North Carolina has seen 23 cases, and New York has diagnosed at least 58, according to USA Today. Opponents of vaccinations often cite religious beliefs or a fear that the vaccinations aren't safe. For example, parents heard conflicting information about a link between the MMR (measles-mumps-rubella) vaccinations and autism. However, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention notes there is no scientifically proved link.

Other opponents say that vaccinations aren't needed because the diseases have disappeared. Scientists dispute that notion, noting that the diseases still exist, but vaccinations have reduced cases of them. Supporters say that the benefits far outweigh the risks of any possible reactions, and that the potential complications from measles are reason enough to get the vaccination. Some of the diseases are still common in other parts of the world, which means that travelers could bring them back to the U.S. An unvaccinated population would be at risk of infection, the American Academy of Pediatrics notes. In our opinion, keeping a child safe and healthy is of the utmost importance, and vaccinations play a vital role in that. And with vaccinations, the benefits extend past one's individual family and to the community as a whole, preventing infections from spreading, as happened in the Texas outbreak. Parents need to make sure their children receive their vaccinations, both as infants and again as teens. It's critical to keep them and our community healthy.

--
Communicated by:
