[6] USA (TX)
Date: Fri 6 Sep 2013
Source: Healio [edited]
http://www.healio.com/pediatrics/vaccine-preventable-diseases/news/online/%7Bb45a0ecc-7e02-4a33-85c0-f54c888ab9a8%7D/measles-outbreak-in-texas-causes-concern-in-oklahoma


As of 16 Aug 2013, there have been 11 cases of measles this year [2013] in Texas, 6 of which occurred in the past month, according to a press release from the Texas Department of State Health Services. The most recently confirmed cases come out of Tarrant County, and the others were from Dallas, Denton and Harris counties. A health alert has been issued, and officials are urging everyone to be immunized against measles.

The Oklahoma State Department of Health is alerting Oklahoma health care providers to consider measles when diagnosing patients with compatible symptoms who have traveled to the North Texas area 18 days before symptom onset. "We are worried about the current outbreak of measles in Texas because measles is very contagious, spreads like wildfire, and can be very serious," said Lori Linstead, director of the Immunization Service at the Oklahoma State Department of Health.

