Oceania
----------
[8] Australia (QL)
Date: Fri 6 Sep 2013
Source: The Courier Mail [abbreviated & edited]
http://www.perthnow.com.au/news/national/gold-coast-mother-of-an-unvaccinated-child-is-among-latest-measles-cases/story-fnii5v6y-1226713572605


Queensland has recorded 2 more cases of the highly infectious measles virus, one of them a young mother with an unvaccinated child. Public health specialists are concerned about the potential for the serious virus to spread, with Queensland Health notified of 6 cases in the past month. Alerts have been sent to general practitioners, public and private hospitals, and pathology laboratories to be on the lookout for possible cases, given the recent cluster.

One of the 2 latest cases, a man in his 30s, had visited the Ipswich Hospital 3 times recently and had travelled on a train, potentially exposing dozens of people to the disease. A Gold Coast mum has also been diagnosed, triggering concerns for her unvaccinated child. Public health officials are trying to trace how they caught the potentially deadly infection to determine whether the cases are linked.

A 17-year-old Caboolture High schoolgirl had been to 2 Gold Coast theme parks and to see Grease, the musical at the Queensland Performing Arts Centre in Brisbane, without knowing she had the virus. Queensland Health's communicable diseases unit acting senior director Stephen Lambert said public health officials were trying to alert anyone who had been in contact with the latest cases.

Two doses of the vaccine are necessary to be fully protected. Dr Lambert said measles could be a serious illness with a 3rd of young adults diagnosed requiring admission to hospital. Complications can include encephalitis, or swelling of the brain, which can be fatal. Dr Lambert described measles as "probably the most transmissible virus for humans." He said the virus was so easily spread, people could catch it from someone even 2 hours after the infected person had left a room. The last big measles epidemic in Queensland was in 1994 when 2345 cases were recorded.

[Byline: Janelle Miles]

